[normal]Q. What global coordination and action is required to fight antimicrobial resistance and is the UK contributing enough towards cross-border initiatives?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]UK 1970 - The solution - Swann recommendations:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]EU 2006. Ban of use of growth promoters in animal feeds [bold]‘Regulation 1831/2003/EC on additives for use in animal nutrition’ [bold]‘This regulation will strengthen the EU’s rules on the safety of animal feed and complete the EU ban on the use of antibiotics as growth promoters Both these objectives are of major importance to the EU’s food safety strategy and indeed to wider considerations of animal health’
[normal] [bold]David Byrne, EU Commissioner for Health and Consumer Protection, 2006 [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]UK Chief Medical Officer Reports 2009, 2011 [bold]‘
[normal]There should be a ban on the use of certain types of antibiotics (quinolones and cephalosporins) in animals, in order to protect their activity in humans’ 
[normal]Sir Liam Donaldson, CMO, 2009 [bold]‘[bold]N
[normal]ational approach to tackling antimicrobial resistance should be managed jointly between DH and Defra to ensure that a comprehensive integrated programme is developed’. 
[normal]Dame Sally Davies, CMO, 2013 [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]European Food Safety Authority (EFSA), 2011 [bold]Scientific Opinion on the public health risks of bacterial strains producing ESBLsand/or AmpC β-lactamases in food and food-producing animals [bold]‘A highly effective control option would be to stop all uses of cephalosporins/systemically active 3rd/4th generation cephalosporins, or to restrict their use (use only to be allowed under specific circumstances)’. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]European Parliament October 2011 [bold]‘European Parliament calls upon the European Commission to make legislative proposals to phase out the prophylactic use of antibiotics in livestock farming in the EU’ 
[normal]European Parliament, 27 October 2011 [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]SANCO strategy on Antimicrobial Resistance[bold]5-year strategy presented on European Antibiotic Awareness Day,18 November 2011 [bold] [bold]Holistic approach: public health, food safety, consumer safety, environment, animal health and welfare as well as non-therapeutic use of antimicrobials 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]WHO Europe strategy on antibiotic resistance [bold]Seven action areas: [bold]1. Promote national coordination 
[normal]2. Strengthen surveillance 
[normal]3. Promote rational use of antibiotics, including surveillance of antibiotic consumption 
[normal]4. Improve infection control and stewardship of antibiotic use in health care settings 
[normal]5. Promote surveillance, prevention and control of antibiotic resistance in the food chain 
[normal]6. Promote research and innovation on new antibiotics 
[normal]7. Improve awareness on antibiotic use and risk of increasing resistance 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fighting antibiotic resistance a priority for WHO/Europe European strategy under development 
[normal]2011 publication suggests actions for tackling antibiotic resistance from a food safety perspective [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Key messages for countries [bold]1. Improve overall coordination 
[normal]2. Improve regulatory framework 
[normal]3. Reduce the need for and promote prudent use of antibiotics 
[normal]4. Improve surveillance 
[normal]5. Advocate and communicate 
[normal]6. Build capacity and provide training 
[normal]7. Address knowledge gaps and research needs 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]WHO/FAO/OIE achievements on AMR since 1997 [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Critically-Important Antimicrobials (CIAs) WHO, 2007, 2009, 2011 [bold]e.g. Quinolones / flouroquinolones 3rd / 4th generation cephalosporins Carbapenams 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Codex: [bold]ad hoc [bold]Intergovernmental Task Force on AMR, 2007-2010[bold] 
[normal]Objectives [bold]1. To assess the risks to human health associated with the presence in food and feed of antimicrobial resistant organisms, antimicrobial resistant genes or residues of antimicrobials 
[normal]2. To develop risk management advice based on that assessment to reduce such a risk 
[normal]Outcome: Guidelines for the Risk Analysis of Foodborne Antimicrobial Resistance [bold]Codex Alimentarius: Strategic Plan 2008-2013[bold] 
[normal]Develop guidance for safe and prudent non-human antimicrobial usage for containment of resistance [bold]&#xa0;[bold]Description: [bold]Develop guidance within the remit of Codex mandate for safe and prudent antimicrobial usage for containment of resistance in food production which focuses on public health, is based on sound science and follows risk analysis principles, and takes into account the work of other international organizations. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Timeline: [bold]Completion by 2011 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Responsible parties: [bold]Existing relevant Codex Committees, 
[normal]ad hoc 
[normal]Intergovernmental Task Force on Antimicrobial Resistance Codex Alimentarius: Strategic Plan 2008-2013 
