[normal]RUMA [bold]Press statement 26 March 2013 [bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Preventive treatment (sometimes referred to as Prophylaxis) [bold]‘Treatment with antibiotics of an animal or a group of animals, before clinical signs of infectious disease, in order to prevent the occurrence of disease or infection’. 
[normal]•
[normal]Must only be applied to animals diagnosed at high risk of bacterial disease, [bold]•
[normal]Must only occur under prescription by veterinarian on basis of epidemiological and clinical knowledge, [bold]•
[normal]Must not be applied systematically or routinely, [bold]•
[normal]Must not be used to compensate for poor hygiene or for inadequate husbandry conditions, or where improvements in animal husbandry could reduce need for antibiotic treatment. [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Food industry perspective[bold]The British Poultry Council have introduced a voluntary ban on the use of fluoroquinolones and 3rd and 4th generation cephalosporins in poultry production from January 2012. 
